          "title": "Grace through scandalous ancestry — Tamar, Achar, and the Egyptian",
          "body": "The Chronicler does not launder the genealogy. Er is wicked; the LORD kills him (2:3). Perez and Zerah are born from Judah's incestuous relationship with his daughter-in-law Tamar — a story the Chronicler barely tells but unmistakably invokes (2:4; Genesis 38). Achar is named 'the troubler of Israel' who 'violated the ban' (2:7) — the man whose sin caused Israel's defeat at Ai (Joshua 7). And in the Jerahmeel branch, the genealogy incorporates Jarha the Egyptian slave (2:34-35) through whom a twelve-generation line descends. These are not flaws the Chronicler could not edit out; they are features he chose to include. The theological point is severe and comforting simultaneously: God's purposes advance not through human perfection but through divine sovereignty that works around, through, and despite human failure and moral complexity. The same grace that ran through Tamar's scandalous birth of Perez runs through the whole genealogy. Matthew will make this explicit by naming Tamar in the genealogy of Jesus (Matthew 1:3)."
