          "body": "The chapter's closing verses (2:42-55) do something unusual: they name towns, territories, and clans rather than individual persons. Bethlehem, Hebron, Ziph, Bethzur, Kiriath-jearim — these are not merely place names; they are land claims. The Chronicler is writing for returnees who need to know which tribe, which clan, and which family belongs where. By embedding geographic names within genealogical lists, he provides the post-exilic community with a land-allocation guide in narrative form. The same logic drives Ezra and Nehemiah, where genealogical lists determine who may serve as priests (Ezra 2:61-63) and who may reclaim specific property (Nehemiah 7:5). But the theological dimension runs deeper: the land is the inheritance promised to Abraham's seed (Genesis 15:18-21), and these genealogies assert that the seed has not been destroyed. Exile was not annihilation. The children of those carried to Babylon have returned, can name their ancestors, and can identify their land. The genealogy is the deed to the inheritance."
