          "body": "The chapter's closing verse (2:55) introduces 'the Kenites who came from Hammath, the father of the house of Rechab' — a non-Israelite people group incorporated into Judah's genealogical record. Earlier, Jarha the Egyptian slave (2:34-35) had been incorporated through marriage into the Sheshan line. These inclusions are theologically significant and structurally deliberate. The Chronicler's Israel is not an ethnically closed community; it is a covenant community capable of including those who attach themselves to it through loyalty and marriage. The Kenites had a history of covenant friendship with Israel (Judges 1:16; 1 Samuel 15:6); the Rechabites would be celebrated in Jeremiah 35 for their radical obedience. By placing them at the close of Judah's genealogy, the Chronicler signals that the covenant family is wider than bloodline alone — a theological insight that reaches its fullest expression when the gospel of the Son of David is proclaimed to every nation (Matthew 28:19; Revelation 5:9)."
